<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-449-001  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 449 001.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: Russian programmers to translate computer docs.andO;(documentation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Language TranslationSoviet UnionComputer industrySoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: RUSSIAN PROGRAMMERS TO TRANSLATE COMPUTER DOCS MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990AUG 7 (NB) -- The Moscow-based youth computer center Variant can translatecomputer documentation into Russian for a very nominal fee.andM;Dimitry Pashkov, Variant's executive told Newsbytes that although some othertranslation services are available, they are either non-Russian or employnon-computer literate personnel.andP;  &quot;As a result, what they produce looks likeanything but software documentation,&quot; he said.andM;Variant's advantage is that the youth center can take on work nobody wants inthe Soviet market, Pashkov stressed.andP;  This includes projects that require alot of work and are very time-consuming.andP;  &quot;And our young people aren't highlypaid.&quot;andM;The center, located in a Moscow suburb is the only place with publiclyavailable computers in the area.andP;  It has attracted a lot of people who wantto take advantage of its services.andP;  According to Pashkov, Variant people,most of whom are programmers fluent in languages, can translate documentationinto complete Ventura files.andP;  &quot;We never charge a lot,&quot; he concluded.andM;Variant's experience in such work has included several dozen computer andsoftware manuals for Atari users.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19900806/Press contact: Dimitry Pashkov, Variant, phone +7095 429-1944, fax +7 095 420-5311)</TEXT></DOC>